        "py/object": "feedparser.FeedParserDict",
        "updated": "2010-01-15T13:19:05Z",
        "subtitle": "<p>I am right now working on a high-traffic project that will run in a sandbox that doesn't allow me to pull third party JavaScript or use canvas/Flash. Yet I need to generate bar charts from a set of data.</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://icant.co.uk/csscharts\"><img src=\"http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4034/4275838221_5ed55f57a6.jpg\" alt=\"Pure CSS bar charts\" /></a></p>\n<p>The solution to me was to create the charts from HTML using CSS. There have been some <a href=\"http://meyerweb.com/eric/css/edge/bargraph/demo.html\">solutions</a> <a href=\"http://www.splintered.co.uk/experiments/archives/css_bar_graphs/\">for</a> <a href=\"http://www.standards-schmandards.com/exhibits/barchart/\">this</a> <a href=\"http://www.cssplay.co.uk/menu/barchart.html\">problem</a> <a href=\"http://speckyboy.com/2009/02/04/16-usable-css-graph-and-bar-chart-tutorials-and-techniques/\">already</a> but I wanted something very simple and easy to maintain. Hence all the markup I am using is this:</p>\n<div><a href=\"javascript:void(0);\">PLAIN TEXT</a></div>\n<div><span>XML:</span>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<div><span><span>&lt;ul<span>&gt;</span></span></span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span><span>&lt;li<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;span<span>&gt;</span></span></span>400<span><span>&lt;/span<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;/li<span>&gt;</span></span></span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span><span>&lt;li<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;span<span>&gt;</span></span></span>20<span><span>&lt;/span<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;/li<span>&gt;</span></span></span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span><span>&lt;li<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;span<span>&gt;</span></span></span>30<span><span>&lt;/span<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;/li<span>&gt;</span></span></span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span><span>&lt;li<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;span<span>&gt;</span></span></span>233<span><span>&lt;/span<span>&gt;</span></span></span><span><span>&lt;/li<span>&gt;</span></span></span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span><span>&lt;/ul<span>&gt;</span></span></span> </div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Instead of hard-coding any of the trickery necessary I wrote a PHP script to generate the HTML, the styles and do all the math. So all that is needed to render one of the charts is the following code:</p>\n<div><a href=\"javascript:void(0);\">PLAIN TEXT</a></div>\n<div><span>PHP:</span>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<div><span>&lt;?php</span> </div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>$values</span> = <span>'400,20,30,233,312,78,20,67'</span>;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>$height</span> = <span>100</span>;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>$width</span> = <span>600</span>;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>$bargap</span> = <span>0</span>;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>include</span><span>(</span><span>'csscharts.php'</span><span>)</span>;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>?&gt;</span> </div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>Of course, this can also be turned into a web service - you can get the chart with the following URL:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://icant.co.uk/csscharts/csscharts.php?values=400,20,30,233,312,78,20,67&height=100&width=600&bargap=0\">http://icant.co.uk/csscharts/csscharts.php?values=400,20,30,233,312,78,20,67&amp;height=100&amp;width=600&amp;bargap=0</a></p>\n<p>And if you specify JSON as the format you get it with a <code>callback</code> to a function called <code>csscharts</code>:</p>\n<p><a href=\"http://icant.co.uk/csscharts/csscharts.php?values=400,20,30,233,312,78,20,67&format=json\">http://icant.co.uk/csscharts/csscharts.php?values=400,20,30,233,312,78,20,67&amp;format=json</a></p>\n<div><a href=\"javascript:void(0);\">PLAIN TEXT</a></div>\n<div><span>JAVASCRIPT:</span>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<div>csscharts<span>(</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>{</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 \u00a0 chart:<span>&quot;&lt;ul class=<span>\\\"</span>barchart<span>\\\"</span> [\u2026 the rest of the html \u2026]&lt;/ul&gt;&quot;</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>}</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>)</span> </div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>That way you can use it in JavaScript:</p>\n<div><a href=\"javascript:void(0);\">PLAIN TEXT</a></div>\n<div><span>JAVASCRIPT:</span>\n<div>\n<div>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<div>&lt;script&gt;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>function</span> csscharts<span>(</span>o<span>)</span><span>{</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 <span>var</span> container = document.<span>getElementById</span><span>(</span><span>'container'</span><span>)</span>;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>\u00a0 c.<span>innerHTML</span> = o.<span>chart</span> + c.<span>innerHTML</span>;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div><span>}</span></div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>&lt;/script&gt;</div>\n</li>\n<li>\n<div>&lt;script src=<span>&quot;http://icant.co.uk/csscharts/csscharts.php?values=400,20,30,233,312,78,20,67&amp;format=json&quot;</span>&gt;&lt;/script&gt; </div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>You can <a href=\"http://icant.co.uk/csscharts/csscharts-demo.php\">see some demos here</a>, get <a href=\"http://icant.co.uk/csscharts/\">detailed info about the CSS trickery used</a> and of course <a href=\"http://github.com/codepo8/CSScharts\">download the code on GitHub.</a>\n<div>\n<a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/ajaxian?a=R11_svY5jUc:vtoe9hBdr1I:yIl2AUoC8zA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/ajaxian?d=yIl2AUoC8zA\" border=\"0\" /></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/ajaxian?a=R11_svY5jUc:vtoe9hBdr1I:7Q72WNTAKBA\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/ajaxian?d=7Q72WNTAKBA\" border=\"0\" /></a> <a href=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/ajaxian?a=R11_svY5jUc:vtoe9hBdr1I:D7DqB2pKExk\"><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~ff/ajaxian?i=R11_svY5jUc:vtoe9hBdr1I:D7DqB2pKExk\" border=\"0\" /></a>\n</div></p>",
